erton, Somerset, England":"Happerton, Somerset, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1294–1327":"1294–1327","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1324–1356":"1324–1356","1331–Female":"1331–Deceased","1327":"1327","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","about 1327":"about 1327","1356":"1356","1299":"1299","1331":"1331","1294":"1294","Halberton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Halberton, Devon, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Halberton, Somerset, England":"Happerton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dunn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Duinn</b>, <b>Ó Doinn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Donn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘brown-haired’ or ‘chieftain’. Compare   Dunne  . This name has sometimes been Anglicized as   Brown  .","English: nickname for a dark complexioned or swarthy man, from Middle English <i>dun</i> ‘dun, dark’ (Old English <i>dunn</i> ‘dull brown’).","Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus, named with Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘fort’. Compare   Dun  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dunne","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Cahal, Eamonn, Grainne.","Chinese: variant of   Dunn  .","German (<b>Dünne</b>): nickname for a slender, skinny person, from Middle High German <i>dünne</i> ‘thin’."]},{"name":"Brown","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: generally a nickname referring to the color of the hair or complexion, Middle English <i>br(o)un</i>, from Old English <i>brūn</i> or Old French <i>brun</i>. This word is occasionally found in Old French, Middle English and Old Norse as a personal name or byname (Middle English personal name <i>Brun</i>, <i>Broun</i>, ancient Germanic <i>Bruno</i>, Old English <i>Brūn</i>, or possibly Old Norse <i>Brúnn</i> or <i>Brúni</i>). <i>Brun-</i> was also an ancient Germanic name-forming element. Some instances of Old English <i>Brūn</i> as a personal name may therefore be short forms of compound names such as <i>Brūngar</i>, <i>Brūnwine</i>, etc. As a Scottish and Irish name, it sometimes represents a translation of Gaelic <i>Donn</i> (see below). <i>Brown</i> (including in the senses below) is the fourth most frequent surname in the US. It is also very common among African Americans and Native Americans (see also 5 below).","Irish and Scottish: adopted for <b>Ó Duinn</b> (see   Dunn  ) or for any of the many Irish and Scottish Gaelic names containing the element <i>donn</i> ‘brown-haired’ (also meaning ‘chieftain’), for example   Donahue  .","Irish: phonetic Anglicization of <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhnaigh</b>; see   Breheny  ."]},{"name":"Don","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Agustin, Jose, Miguel, Pablo, Ramon, Ruben, Adriana, Ausencio, Eduardo, Enrique, Erasmo, Francisco.","English and Scottish: variant of   Dunn  .","English and Scottish: variant of   Dun  , a habitational name from Dun in Angus, Scotland."]},{"name":"Done","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Alfredo, Angel, Berto, Cristobal, Dinora, Eloisa, Francisco, Generoso, Gustavo, Juan.","English: variant of <b>Donne</b>, itself a variant of   Dunn  ."]},{"name":"Dunsford","meanings":["English: habitational name from Dunsford in Devon, from the genitive case of the Old English personal name <i>Dunn</i> (see   Dunn  ) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. Although Dunsforth in Yorkshire also gave rise to the surname, it appears not to have survived the medieval period."]},{"name":"Dunford","meanings":["habitational name from Dunford Bridge, in Thurlstone (Yorkshire), so called from the river <i>Don</i> (a British name possibly meaning ‘river’) + Old English <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, or from Dunford House in Methley (Yorkshire), named in Old English as ‘Dunn's ford’ (see   Dunn   2).","variant of <b>Durnford</b>, a habitational name from Durnford in Wiltshire, arising from Old English <i>dierne</i> + <i>ford</i> ‘hidden ford’. Alternatively, the name may perhaps arise from Dunford, alias Durnford, in Addlestone (Surrey).","English:"]},{"name":"Donn","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Chaim, Isaak, Meyer, Zorach.","English (Lancashire) and Scottish (Caithness): variant of   Dunn  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Don  ."]},{"name":"Dunson","meanings":["English and Scottish: probably a patronymic from   Dunn   2 or4. Compare   Donson  ."]},{"name":"Dun","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Dun in Angus.","English: variant of   Dunn  .","Dutch: nickname from Middle Dutch <i>dun</i> ‘thin’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Dunn was born in 1294, in Halberton, Devon, England, United Kingdom. He married Elinor de Knovill about 1327, in England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died in 1327, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1294–1327":"1294–1327","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1324–1356":"1324–1356","1331–Female":"1331–Surnud","1327":"1327","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","about 1327":"umbes 1327","1356":"1356","1299":"1299","1331":"1331","1294":"1294","Halberton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Halberton, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Halberton, Somerset, England":"Happerton, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1294–1327":"1294–1327","1299–1368":"1299–1368","1324–1356":"1324–1356","1331–Female":"1331–Kuollut","1327":"1327","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","about 1327":"noin 1327","1356":"1356","1299":"1299","1331":"1331","1294":"1294","Halberton, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Halberton, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","Halberton, Somerset, England":"Happerton, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt 